COMPILE INSTRUCTIONS:

  Requires a C++17-capable compiler (g++ 7+ recommended) and GNU make.

  To build:
      make

  To remove build artifacts:
      make clean

  This produces the executable: ./lxe

OPERATING INSTRUCTIONS:
 
 Usage:
      ./lxe <source_file.sic>

  Arguments:
      <source_file.sic>   Path to a SIC/XE assembly source file (required)

  Output files (written to the same directory as the source file):
      <basename>.st       Symbol/literal table dump (sorted SYMTAB + LITTAB)
      <basename>.l        Listing file -- line numbers, addresses, object codes,
                          and source text (produced after Pass 2)


DESIGN DECISIONS:

  1. Single Assembler class split across four .cpp files
     The entire assembler lives in one class (declared in assembler.h) but its
     implementation is divided by responsibility: Pass 1, Pass 2, symbol-table
     output, and listing output. This keeps each file focused without
     introducing multiple classes or a complex module hierarchy.

  2. Intermediate file used to bridge passes
     Pass 1 writes a .int file and populates an in-memory lines[] vector.
     Pass 2 operates on that same vector (plus the populated SYMTAB/LITTAB),
     matching the classic two-pass assembler model described in the textbook.

  3. Literal pool (LITTAB) with deferred address assignment
     Literals are collected during Pass 1 and assigned addresses only when an
     LTORG directive is encountered. injectLiteralLines() inserts
     synthetic *LTORG* entries into lines[] so Pass 2 can emit object code for
     them in the correct position.

  4. PC-relative preferred, base-relative fallback (Format 3/4)
     assembleFormat3or4() first attempts PC-relative displacement; if out of
     range and BASE has been set, it falls back to base-relative. Format 4
     (extended) bypasses both and uses a 20-bit absolute address with the e-bit
     set.

  5. Addressing mode flags parsed from operand string parseOperand()
	 strips #, @, and ,X from the raw operand text and sets
     boolean flags (immediate, indirect, indexed), separating operand
	 parsing cleanly from instruction encoding.


KNOWN DEFICIENCIES / BUGS:

	- None known at this time.

LESSONS LEARNED:

	- This assignment reinforced the concepts behind two pass assemblers and
	  why they are necessary in order to resolve symbols.
	- How the LITTAB defers adress assignment until LTORG / END.
	- Small typos in method names can cause hard to diagnose linker errors 
	  not just obvious compile errors. (assemblerFormat2 vs assembleFormat2)
		



